(50, 201575235, '2023-07-04 11:22:21', '/gpt code java catch', 'To catch and handle exceptions in Java, you can use the try-catch block. \n\nHere is an example of how to use it:\n\n```java\ntry {\n    // Code that may throw an exception\n    int result = divideNumbers(10, 0);\n    System.out.println(\"Result: \" + result);\n} catch (ArithmeticException e) {\n    // Exception handler for ArithmeticException\n    System.out.println(\"Cannot divide by zero!\");\n    e.printStackTrace();\n} catch (Exception e) {\n    // Generic exception handler\n    System.out.println(\"An error occurred!\");\n    e.printStackTrace();\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, we have a method `divideNumbers()` that may throw an `ArithmeticException` if the second parameter is zero. In the `try` block, we call this method and assign the result to a variable. If the exception is thrown, the control flow jumps to the relevant `catch` block.\n\nYou can have multiple `catch` blocks to handle different types of exceptions. The more specific exception types should be listed first, and more generic ones (like `Exception`) should be listed at the end. If an exception is not caught by any specific `catch` block, it will be caught by the generic `catch` block (if provided).\n\nWithin the `catch` block, you can handle the exception as needed. In the example above, we simply print an error message and stack trace using the `printStackTrace()` method.\n\nRemember to always handle exceptions that you expect to be thrown to prevent unexpected program termination.'),
